1: The first piece of the puzzle<br>
<br>
Neriak is an ancient city, one that has been home to the Tier’Dal since their beginnings as a creation of Innoruuk’s own hate. It has seen many changes, ancient buildings still stand, but the city has destroyed and remade itself countless times. As such, there are parts that have been forgotten. Many do not have a slightest inkling of how far into Norrath the tunnels of the ancient city reach. Indeed, beyond the Foreigner’s City and even past the Third Gate, the Tier’Dal empire burrows deep into the stone and dirt. Some of these places had uses once, as tunnels for escape, that have caved in, or places for solitude when a noble sought the safety of home without the intrusions of city life. A few caverns still maintain a cause, the hiding places for those who practice arts forbidden by Tier’Dal society, as well as execution grounds for Heretics among the Dark Elves. Huge spiders once climbed these caves, watching over those being punished for their crimes against Neriak, a mass of bodies, hanging encased in webbing over a darkened lake of water. Though the spiders have long since moved on to new feeding grounds (for there are now executions nearly every week) the remains of their meals still hang in the forgotten caverns.<br>
<br>
It was in one of these caverns Guronk found something. He was a simple troll, quite lost and very aggravated at his current situation. Neriak was new for him, the Dark elves had taken his race into the Foreign Quarter when they were overthrown by an army of frogloks. As Guronk would say they were <br>
<br>
‘A buncha weak lil toadies who onlee beatz us cuz dey so small we didna see em till it wuz to late.’<br>
<br>
Guronk’s new home was comfortable though, despite not being near a swamp. It did allow him all the joys of home, drinking, feasting, and of course, inflicting pain. However with his new home came new responsibilities, he was required to run errands for one of the Noble Houses of Tier’Dal society. It was his most recent errand that had sent him into the water’s of a well in the Foreign city, and had led him here.<br>
<br>
“Troll! Hey you! Big oaf!”<br>
<br>
Guronk blinked looking up at the Dark Elf addressing him, as he was busy cleaning dried blood from under his fingernails, a look of confusion crossing his large features.<br>
<br>
“Come here greenskin. Help me with something.”<br>
<br>
Guronk nodded, and finished removing a bit of meat from underneath a long yellowed fingernail, then stood and came over to where the Elf was standing, staring into a well. Another dark elf was standing nearby with a huge grin on his face apparently very amused at something.<br>
<br>
“Waz can I do fer ya sur?”<br>
<br>
The dark elf pointed into the well, and Guronk bent over to try and see what the elf was pointing at.<br>
<br>
“I dropped a wand in there, I need it back. Can you get it for me troll?”<br>
<br>
Guronk couldn’t see anything in the depths of the water, just darkness. He stood back up (as straight as a troll can stand, his posture left him always slouching) and reached up to scratch the back of his large head.<br>
<br>
“Iz don see nuttin in there.”<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf who was smiling burst into laughter, causing the first to swing a hand at him in a slap. The second elf danced back easily dodging, his laughter slowly subsiding.<br>
<br>
“But it’s in there all the same. Get it for me will you? I’ve got some dwarf meat you can have when you find it.”<br>
<br>
Guronk shrugged and bent back over the well, it was small for a creature of his size, it would be a tight fit getting in, but he supposed he could do it if he had too. Dwarf meat was a treat he hadn’t had in ages. He stood up once more, towering over the dark elves and shrugged.<br>
<br>
“OK Guronk gon’ try an help ya find da thing.”<br>
<br>
The short Tier’Dal nodded suddenly smiling.<br>
<br>
“Thank you Guronk. We’ll be waiting in the castle courtyard, I have other business to attend to.”<br>
<br>
Guronk reached up and pulled off his heavy leather shirt and took off his steel toed boots. It had been some time since he had gone for a swim, he figured now would be as good a time as any. He had enjoyed swimming in the swamp of Innothule, hunting wildlife for the fun of the kill. Maybe there were things in the well he could hunt as well. After he found the whatever it was for the darkie, that is. Guronk stepped into the well, and slowly lowered himself in until only his head was out of the water. The well was just wide enough for him to stretch from one end to the other, which made it a little confining but really nothing more than an inconvenience.<br>
<br>
“Ok Iz gon look fer it now.”<br>
<br>
The two dark elves nodded in unison as Guronk took a deep breath and ducked into the water, swimming down as far as he could. Meanwhile, the two dark elves began to place bets on how long it would take the troll to realize he had been sent on an errand that couldn’t be completed, laughing at their triumph over such a trusting creature.<br>
<br>
For a few minutes Guronk explored the well up and down, searching for the wand that wasn’t there, eventually he began to think the errand was pointless. However when he next dived, he found something. A hole in the wall of the well, that fed it water from the underwater stream Neriak sat over. Perhaps the wand had been sucked through the hole Guronk thought. He returned to the surface to take a huge breath of air, then dived down into the depths, his good vision aiding him well even in the darkness of the waters. Guronk swam through the hole and was plunged into darkness, he slowly began to panic as he swam, not being able to find his way back to the well. He followed the tunnel for a ways, slowly running out of breath before finally finding air. The large troll head broke the surface of the water in a spray of droplets as he sucked fresh air into his lungs. Guronk blinked a few times. He was lost, and in a huge cave that stretched into the distance. Above him white bundles of webbing hung, some were low enough for him to reach. He treaded water for a few moments trying to figure out what to do next, dive again and try to find his way back? Or follow the tunnel and hope it led back to Neriak?<br>
<br>
Guronk decided he would rather not risk drowning and so he began to swim following the tunnel. The huge lake in which he had found himself slowly became shallower as he followed the tunnel to its destination. Eventually he was walking on the bottom, and after an hour or so the lake gave way to stone. Still the white bundles hung from the ceiling, motionless in the windless air of the cave. The cave had no end in sight, and with nothing better to do Guronk simply continued to follow it. As he wandered he occasionally looked up, those bundles of webbing were people once he guessed. He could recognize skulls, and other bones inside those bundles, many things had died here, including trolls, ogres and dark elves. It didn’t concern him much. Whatever had killed them seemed long gone.<br>
<br>
Time passed and the tunnel slowly became brighter as he traveled, he had now been lost for over four hours, simply following the tunnel thinking to himself about things of no great importance. In the far distance he could see what looked like the back of a huge building bearing the winged eye of the Dark Elves, Neriak at last! Home was perhaps ten minutes away if he ran, but having found his way back Guronk decided to take his time. He continued to stare upward at the skeletons hanging from the ceiling, in doing so his feet stepped down with a loud crunch on something. Guronk’s reflexes were slow, rather than flinch or hope back at the sound and feeling of something breaking under foot he simply took another step before pausing to see what he had found.<br>
<br>
There were the remains of a corpse on the floor of the tunnel, a dark elf skeleton. Guronk had stepped on one of the decaying leg bones, and snapped it in two. The skeleton was old, but something glimmered in its ribcage. Guronk squatted and peered into the bones, extending one arm and a finger to poke at the object that gleamed within. It was a knife, a well made one at that. There was a ruby in the hilt and gold thread melded into the hilt. The blade was a dark black, and pock marked with blood red flecks, and was fused with one of the ribs. Whoever had died here the ceremonial dagger denoted that this victim was executed for crimes against a noble house. Guronk didn’t know this, to him the blade looked like it would fetch a nice price, or at the very least look good on his wall. With a strong hand he snapped off the rib bone that the blade was fused to and examined it closer. Yes, it would do just fine as either something to sell or a relic he could claim as coming from a foe he had defeated.<br>
<br>
With his newfound treasure Guronk finished walking the rest of the way to the huge building and forced open the musty door who’s hinges were nearly gone from rust and age. It led him into another dark room, which lead to a trapdoor, which in turn opened into the royal palace. Guronk spent another hour or so wandering the hug compound that was the home of the Tier’Dal royal family, now not so worried about being lost. Eventually he was thrown out by some guards who had found him skulking about. Thankfully the guards knew where the exit was better than Guronk, and the simple minded troll made his way home with the treasure he had found in the caverns.<br>
<br>
The next day Guronk went into the city to sell his prize, and it was bought (more or less) for a pretty sum of four hundred platinum. The Dark Elf that had bought it had seen it in Guronk’s hands as he wandered about looking for a place to sell the oddity.<br>
<br>
“Hey troll, may I enquire as to what is that in your hand?”<br>
<br>
Guronk smiled broadly glad to show off his discovery.<br>
<br>
“Yes, I found diz in sum caves, iza pretty dagger stuck inna rib bone.”<br>
<br>
The dark elf extended a hand reaching for the bone.<br>
<br>
“May I see it please?”<br>
<br>
Guronk nodded and handed it to the dark elf who examined it closely and with an appraising eye, he muttered some arcane words and Guronk could feel a spell being cast as the elf’s eyes went wide. The rib bone in his hands began to glow a dull yellow. The dark elf pulled it closer to him shielding it from view. He whispered to Guronk.<br>
<br>
“I’ll give you four hundred platinum for the bone.”<br>
<br>
Guronk grinned so broadly it seemed that his skin was peeling off of his face, he nodded hungrily.<br>
<br>
“Four hundred iz gud!”<br>
<br>
The Tier’Dal pulled out a purse counted the money and gave it to Guronk. Who pocketed it with one hand while wiping his mouth dry with the other (the thought of all the fresh meat, and alcohol he could buy as well as the parties he could throw with the money was causing him to drool just a little). He turned to leave when the dark elf stopped him. Guronk stopped looking confused as the dark elf extended the bone to him.<br>
<br>
“Grab the hilt.”<br>
<br>
Guronk furrowed his eye brows, still confused but did as he was told, he grasped the hilt of the blade that had fused to the rib bone, and as he did so the dark elf wrenched it hard. The hilt snapped from the blade, which remained with the bone, and the dark elf turned and disappeared into the crowd saying over his shoulder.<br>
<br>
“Keep the blade.”<br>
<br>
The dark elf that bought the bone was a necromancer by the name of Dairun, in it he had found a powerful corpse that would serve him well as an undead minion. What he didn’t know was he had also found the first part of a twisted and complicated puzzle.<br>
<br>
