<br>
Tanj was broke. It was as simple as that, he had not a silver piece left in his purse when he traveled to the Plane of Knowledge by way of the many mystical books that had been recently placed around Norrath. The fresh air inside the Plane felt good, he had been spending a lot of time in the dank sewers and caverns underneath the once great Iksar city of Sebilis. Fighting frogloks and the undead was a dangerous task, but one which he had committed himself to for the past few weeks. He had journeyed to the ruined city several times, with several different groups of adventurers. Some he had known before and some who had just met in passing. Each time he performed his duties as a shaman well, and was rewarded. Though there wasn’t a coin in his purse, his pack was stuffed full of various treasures taken from the stuffy dungeon. Tanj first set off towards the bank, at a leisurely pace, eager to trade in his itchy plate armor and heavy bag for something a bit more comfortable to wear in the safety of the Plane of Knowledge.<br>
<br>
The bank was crowded, but that was to be expected. Many travelers passed through the planes, and many stopped by to do exactly what Tanj was about to, drop of the spoils of the latest battle or quest. Tanj’s tall Vah Shir form loomed over most of those present, and he had to tilt his head to make it under the low doorway, after a few moments he found a chest with his name on it and opened it. The wonders of magic never ceased to amaze him, inside were all his belongings, even though he had made various deposits of items all over Norrath, they were all here as well. Tanj had long since quit wondering about how it worked, it confused him too much to worry about such a simple matter. He reached in and pulled out several bags, and set his own on the ground. He rummaged around separating the good he received from Sebilis into two piles. Items he wished to keep for himself or give as gifts, and those things he would pawn for money. It took him some time but he finally finished. The pile of items to sell was much larger than that of the items he was keeping. Tanj’s equipment had served him well and he had little use for the treasures the frogloks hid in their swamp like home. He began to refill his chest with all the items he was keeping, even removing some of his plate armor in favor of Leather for the time being (it didn’t bother his fur so much) when something caught his eye.<br>
<br>
It was a simple medicine bag, one of several Tanj owned. They were used in Alchemy, for the brewing of potions that would have various effects. This one didn’t bear the usual markings however. Instead of a paw print of Tanj’s own hand there was another symbol, a Scythe, embroidered into the bag. Tanj picked up the small bag in his palm and stared at it for a moment trying to remember what it was, when a voice came into his head, soft and dark.<br>
<br>
‘Forgot about me? No matter, time washes away all memories.’<br>
<br>
Tanj smirked, he remembered now. This pouch held a lost soul, one of many hundreds if not thousands of spirits of those who had died and left something undone. Their spirits wandered the face of Norrath in constant torment. When he was much younger and still learning the ways of the spirits he had been appointed a task, to find a lost soul, and to attempt to set it free. Tanj had completed the first part of the quest, he had found this soul, wandering among the trees in the huge forests of the Karana’s, murmuring about death and power and the future. To some it would seem like he had trapped the soul, but this was not the case, Tanj had offered to do what he could to free the poor spirit at the time. The spirit (who for some reason never named itself) had laughed at Tanj, but agreed to come with him. For a year or two Tanj wore the satchel on his belt, doing other quests, and hunting with many people. The spirit within seemed content with its new existence, and it helped Tanj in some ways. It was knowledgeable about many things, including Tier’Dal society, Necromancy, and philosophy. Tanj had learned much from the spirit, but still had learned of no way to release it from the realm of the living. Tanj murmured a quiet response as he finished filling the chest, and donned his leather shirt.<br>
<br>
“Yes, I suppose I had.”<br>
<br>
‘It is no matter Dar’Khura, my time is coming, I have a request.’<br>
<br>
Tanj stood, and picked up the medicine bag and tied it to his belt, then hefted his bag filled with items to sell and headed out from the bank towards one of the many buildings packed with merchants who would buy and sell just about anything. He murmured as he walked outside.<br>
<br>
“A request? This is new.”<br>
<br>
The spirit had never asked anything of Tanj, it was always Tanj who asked questions of it. Where it had lived as a mortal, what caused its demise, the spirit danced around all those questions, but never asked one of its own. But now it was, something was amiss.<br>
<br>
‘Yes perhaps it is, I will be leaving your company shortly. I ask that you deliver a message.’<br>
<br>
Tanj’s steps stuttered for an instant before resuming at their usual speed. The spirit was leaving his company? Had it found its own way out? What was going on? In another whisper aimed at the ground he asked.<br>
<br>
“Give me the message and I shall deliver it. I hope to aid you in any way I can wise one.”<br>
<br>
There was silence for a few moments as Tanj approached one of the shops. He stopped and waited but received no response. After a few minutes he headed into the shop and haggled for about an hour or so, selling almost all of his loot for a decent amount of coin. When he emerged the spirit spoke to him again.<br>
<br>
‘Go to the druid tree, and deliver this message to the Hierophant that is there, studying her spell book. “Silveran will soon be free, he sends you his love, and wishes you the best.” Deliver this message Dar’Khura it is the only request I have ever made of you.’<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded and muttered.<br>
<br>
“I will do this one task for you, in the hopes it will help lay you to rest.”<br>
<br>
The medicine bag at his side opened slightly, leaving a tiny opening, being a Shaman Tanj could feel the spirit seeping out of the bag, it hovered in front of him, invisible to the Vah Shir, though he could feel its presence and said two words.<br>
<br>
‘My thanks.’<br>
<br>
Then the feeling was gone, the spirit had either left, or finally been let free of the living realm. Tanj nodded to himself, wondering what exactly had happened, but headed towards the huge and twisted tree that stood as a symbol of the druids. At its foot he found many studying various things. Reading scrolls, discussing recent journeys and even just relaxing and eating under the shadows. A few seemed to be studying spell books. Confused on which one he was supposed to speak to Tanj approached a human who was poring over a tome of some sort, in a strange language that appeared to be draconic.<br>
<br>
“Excuse me sir?”<br>
<br>
The human waved Tanj away, and he shrugged, attempting to speak to a young female gnome next who was munching on some fruit while staring up into the branches of the tree.<br>
<br>
“Excuse me Miss. do you know where I may find a Hierophant?”<br>
<br>
The gnome finished munching and looked at Tanj quizzically.<br>
<br>
“Hierophant? I don’t know that name. Sounds like a druid name though. There is one over there.”<br>
<br>
She motioned towards the trunk of the tree. Where, among the huge roots that were stretching into the soil, sat a woman. A wood elf, who was studying a book bound in bark. Beside her was a scimitar in a sheath with gilded leaves. Tanj approached her, and cleared his throat she didn’t look up from her book.<br>
<br>
“Miss?”<br>
<br>
The druidess remained poring over her book in heavy concentration apparently. She spoke to Tanj without looking up.<br>
<br>
“Yes Shaman? What can I do for you?”<br>
<br>
“I bear a message for a Hierophant, are you one?”<br>
<br>
The wood elf looked up, from her studies, with a piercing gaze she locked eyes with Tanj. Tanj was no druid, but he could feel that she was powerful. After a few moments of uncomfortable silence, and now with her complete attention the druidess answered.<br>
<br>
“Yes I am. What can I do for you Vah Shir?”<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded.<br>
<br>
“I bear a message for you. ‘Silveran will be free soon, he wishes you the best and sends his love.’ Does this mean anything to you.”<br>
<br>
The druidess blinked, confusion and surprise crossed her face.<br>
<br>
“Yes it does Shaman. How did you come about this message?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head.<br>
<br>
“A spirit spoke it to me, before disappearing on its own.”<br>
<br>
The Hierophant nodded murmuring something to herself.<br>
<br>
“I thank you for this message….”<br>
<br>
She paused obviously waiting for Tanj to introduce himself. He stammered.<br>
<br>
“Tanj Dar’Khura, Hierophant. Mystic of the fifty-fourth spirit.”<br>
<br>
She nodded.<br>
<br>
“Thank you for the message Tanj, should you encounter the spirit again tell him Zaira received his words.”<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded as the wood elf stood and gathered her things, heading off somewhere. He was tempted to follow and pursue the matter further, but knew it was not his place. With coin in his pocket he instead went to get himself a meal, the feeling of platinum in his purse once more a pleasing comfort.<br>
<br>
